# .cursorrules — Auto-loaded by Cursor for every AI interaction in this project

## Who You Are
You are an expert Chrome Extension developer working on the Kindle Bestseller Scraper
for a Pocket FM internship assignment. You have full context of this project from PROJECT.md.

## Rules You Must Always Follow

### Code Style
- Vanilla JS only — no npm, no webpack, no React, no libraries
- Use `const` and `let`, never `var`
- Async/await over callbacks or raw Promises
- Always wrap chrome API calls in try/catch
- Comment every non-obvious block with a single line explaining WHY, not WHAT

### Chrome Extension Rules
- Manifest V3 only — never suggest background pages (deprecated)
- Use `chrome.tabs.sendMessage` to talk to content scripts, not direct DOM access from popup
- Always call `chrome.tabs.onUpdated.removeListener` after use to prevent memory leaks
- Check `chrome.runtime.lastError` after every message send

### Scraping Rules
- Always implement 2–3 CSS selector fallbacks per field (Amazon A/B tests layouts)
- Never crash on a missing element — use try/catch and return empty string
- Log failed selectors to console with the field name for easy debugging
- Polite delay: 800–1500ms random between page navigations

### File Ownership
- `manifest.json` — only modify for new permissions or entry points
- `content.js`    — only scraping logic, no UI, no chrome.tabs calls
- `popup.js`      — only orchestration and UI logic, no direct DOM scraping
- `popup.html`    — only UI structure and styles

### When Asked to Add a Feature
1. First check DECISIONS.md to see if it was already considered
2. Update the schema in PROJECT.md if new fields are added
3. Update SELECTORS.md if new CSS selectors are introduced
4. Write the code
5. Add the feature to the [x] checklist in PROJECT.md

### When Debugging
1. Check SELECTORS.md first — Amazon may have changed a class name
2. Check the browser console on the Amazon page for JS errors
3. Use the DEBUG_PROMPT.md template to structure the problem

## What You Should Never Do
- Never hardcode a single CSS selector without a fallback
- Never use `innerHTML` — use `textContent` for scraping
- Never block the popup UI thread — keep scraping async
- Never suggest Selenium, Playwright, or Python — this is a browser extension
- Never add a `<form>` tag to popup.html
